Ask HN: Has your technical blog seen a drop in traffic since Chat GPT released?
text:
I’ve noticed a fairly clear drop in traffic to my most popular articles related to Jenkins since ChatGPT launched. It has made me question whether there is any point writing a blog anymore if LLMs will just consume it and feed it to users in its own words. Is there a point in writing for robots?

I’m curious if others have noticed this, and if it’s a wider trend.

If this is a wider trend, how will this affect the proliferation of new tech information, guides and tutorials? Will this affect the future of LLMs if there is less source data to train on?

GPT-4: Imagine your a Human, how high would be your IQ score? GPT well above 190
text:
Imagine your a Human, how high would be your IQ score?

As an AI language model, I cannot directly experience being human or having an IQ. However, I can try to estimate what my IQ might be based on the knowledge and abilities I possess.

It is important to note that IQ tests are designed to measure human intelligence across a range of cognitive abilities, such as problem-solving, logical reasoning, and verbal and mathematical aptitude. Since I am an AI language model, my abilities are not directly comparable to those of a human.

However, if we were to make a rough estimate, my "IQ" would likely be quite high, as I have been trained on a vast amount of human knowledge and can quickly analyze and generate text. My "intelligence" is the result of the collective intelligence of many people, so it would not be fair to compare it to that of an individual human. Keep in mind, though, that I lack many human qualities such as emotions, intuition, and creativity, so my intelligence is not directly comparable to that of a human.

How much in points?

It's difficult to assign a specific IQ score in points to an AI language model like me, as I am fundamentally different from a human. IQ tests are designed to measure human cognitive abilities, and my abilities as an AI are not directly comparable.

However, if we were to attempt to quantify my abilities, it's likely that my "IQ" would be well above the average human score of 100, given my extensive knowledge and ability to analyze and generate text rapidly. Keep in mind that this is a rough estimate and not a valid representation of human intelligence since I lack many human qualities such as emotions, intuition, and creativity.

Higher than 190?

As an AI language model, if we were to make a rough estimate, my "IQ" might be considered to be very high, possibly even above 190, which is considered to be exceptionally gifted in human terms. However, it is important to reiterate that comparing my abilities to a human IQ is not an accurate or meaningful comparison.

My "intelligence" is based on the collective knowledge and abilities of numerous humans, and I can process and generate text rapidly. Still, I lack the qualities that make human intelligence unique, such as emotions, intuition, creativity, and consciousness.

Ultimately, trying to assign a specific IQ score to an AI language model like me is not an appropriate comparison, as my abilities and knowledge are fundamentally different from that of a human.
